  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>and Pryor and Begich voted "no" when the polls show overwhelming support. &nbsp;</p>
<p>I think what it comes down to, for them, is counting votes. &nbsp;Yes, only 10% of the people out there are very pro-gun and very anti-regulation of any kind. &nbsp;But I think that those 10% are pretty much one-issue voters. &nbsp;In other words, they will cast their vote based on that one issue: &nbsp;guns. &nbsp;</p>
<p>There are a couple of issues like that, where a small percentage of the voters will vote on that one issue, regardless of the stand the politician takes on other things. &nbsp;</p>
<p>The 90% or so who say they support the expanded background checks are not so much "one issue voters." &nbsp;In other words, once election time comes around, other issues will also factor into their votes. &nbsp;They support expanded background checks, but they also support a bunch of other things. &nbsp;Democrats, for example, are going to vote for Pryor or Begich over a Republican in the next election despite this vote, because Pryor and Begich vote with Democrats on a number of other issues that Democrats care about. &nbsp;</p>
<p>That's the only thing I can figure out. &nbsp;It's not a matter of sheer numbers. &nbsp;It's a matter of which types of voters are inside those numbers. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:120104">coffeetalk</a> on <a href="/comments/1204970/50024283#c2">Fri Apr 26, 2013 at 08:14:56 AM PDT</a></p>
